description.undefined: A natural product taxonomy derived from the NPClassifier tool.

abstract.value: An SKOS-based OWL ontology for the structural classification of natural products derived from the NPClassifier tool. This OWL ontology was generated with the script in [scripts folder](scripts/natural_product_taxonomy).

introduction.value: This taxonomy is structured with the SKOS vocabulary. skos:broder is used to represent the hierarchy among Classes, Superclasses and Pathways.  npc:Class, npc:Superclass and npc:Pathway are subclasses of skos:Concept. rdfs:label is assigned for each term of the taxonomy that are instances of one of the subclasses of skos:Concept.

comment.undefined: The highest level of a hierarchical chemical structure classification such as those defined with the NPClassifier, a deep-learning tool for the automated structural classification of natural products (NP) from their counted Morgan fingerprints. The Pathways of NPClassifier consist of seven categories: fatty acids, polyketides, shikimatesâ€“phenylpropanoids, terpenoids, alkaloids, amino acids/peptides, and carbohydrates.

The Superclasses represent subcategories within the Pathways. The categories in the Superclass originate from the general classes of metabolites (e.g., flavonoids, meroterpenoids, or steroids), the general chemical or molecular shapes (e.g., chromanes, phloroglucinols, or macrolides), or biosynthetic information (e.g., tryptophan alkaloids, aromatic polyketides, or pseudo alkaloids).

comment.undefined: The Superclasses are subdivided into Classes that represent specific compound families (e.g., erythromycins, penicillins, or cannabinoids), characteristic functional groups (e.g., chromones, azaphilones, indole alkaloids, or 3-spiro tetramic acids), or scaffold diversity within a Superclass (e.g., flavans, flavones, and chalcones from flavonoids).

definition.value: skos:closeMatch is used to link two concepts that are sufficiently similar that they can be used interchangeably in some information retrieval applications. comment.en: These concept mapping relations mirror semantic relations, and the data model defined below is similar (with the exception of skos:exactMatch) to the data model defined for semantic relations. A distinct vocabulary is provided for concept mapping relations, to provide a convenient way to differentiate links within a concept scheme from links between concept schemes. However, this pattern of usage is not a formal requirement of the SKOS data model, and relies on informal definitions of best practice.
